article.description:
Jocelyn Penn scored a school-record 51
points as No. 16 South Carolina defeated Stetson 101-39 on Saturday
night.
article.headline: Penn breaks Shannon Johnson's scoring mark
article.linkText: Point taken: USC's Penn scores school-record 51 points
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina's Jocelyn Penn broke this
record on her own.

	   Penn's foul shot with four-tenths of a second left gave her 51
points, surpassing the school mark of 50 set by Shannon Johnson in
1996. Penn matched the record on Dec. 4, in a 99-46 victory over
Wofford.

	   But that game against came with its share of critics.

	   Wofford coach Ed Wyant told the Gamecocks' Susan Walvius he was
not happy that her team pressed and fouled during the final minutes
to get Penn more scoring chances.

	   "A lot of what she did tonight, she did on her own," Walvius
said of her senior star after South Carolina's 101-39 win Saturday
night. "Scrapping for rebounds, aggressively
taking the ball to the hole. I'm glad to see her do it, and her
teammates were definitely in tune with the record ... but no, it
wasn't necessarily this team's focus."

	   Penn chased down missed shots and sprinted ahead of defenders
until the very end, and Stetson coach Dee Romine had no complaints
about her achievement.

	   "That's what records are all about, to go for them," Romine
said. "Obviously, their game plan was to try and give her as many
touches to score, and our intention was to try and shut her off."

	   The Gamecocks never have been much of a factor in their first 10
SEC seasons, but for the second straight year they'll enter league
play at 12-1. The biggest reason is Penn, who leads the SEC in
scoring, shooting percentage and steals.

	   Against Stetson (1-9), she was unstoppable, making 19 of 29
shots, grabbing 15 rebounds and getting six steals. Penn put this
one away early, scoring 11 points during a 13-0 first-half run that
turned a two-point deficit into a 21-10 lead for the Gamecocks.

	   After Cristina Ciocan's jumper tied it at 10-10, Penn made a
steal and hit two foul shots. Penn's drive increased the lead to
16-10. Then she made an open 3-pointer and finished her run with an
inside basket with 10:56 left.

	   Her teammates got Penn thinking about a run at the record with
about 10 minutes left and the game out of reach. All Walvius told
her was that South Carolina's men's basketball scoring record was
56, set by John Roche.

	   "I just wanted to work on the things that I needed to work on,
and I was just out there posting up every time," Penn said. "It
definitely feels good."

	   South Carolina point guard Kelly Morrone made apologies for
wanting her good friend to stand alone in Gamecock history.

	   "If you could see how much she's worked and grown since coming
here," Morrone said. "JP definitely should have this."

	   Kristy Brown had 12 points to lead the Hatters, who couldn't
recover against South Carolina's pressure. Penn's push for the
record was all that kept the crowd interested down the stretch.

	   Stetson guard Tashean Thomas said South Carolina players were
discussing the mark on the court, and stopping Penn became the
Hatters' mission.

	   Penn reached 40 points on an inside shot with 6:10 left. A
putback gave her 49 points with two minutes to go, but her shot
with 52 seconds left bounced out.

	   Thomas tried to dribble much of the final minute away. After she
made two foul shots, Thomas ran to deny Penn the ball at midcourt
and was called for a foul with 11.1 seconds left. Penn made the
first foul shot to reach 50, then watched the second attempt bounce
away.

	   Penn tried a heave from the top of the key as the clock wound
down and was bit by two Stetson players, sending her to the line
for a final chance.

	   The crowd and her teammates called for quiet as Penn prepared to
shoot. "Kelly (Morrone) told me to be calm, and just shoot," said
Penn, who was 12-of-15 from the line.

	   Moments later, the record was hers.

	   "I did not want her to get it," said Thomas, who hugged Penn
afterward. "But she deserves it."

	   Stetson, averaging 27 turnovers a game this season, committed 34
in this one, leading to many easy Gamecock baskets -- most of them
by Penn.

	   The Gamecocks open SEC play Thursday night at home against Mississippi State (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP).
